{"title_page": "Gary Beadle", "text_new": "{{short description|British actor|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{For|the reality TV personality|Gaz Beadle}}\n{{EngvarB|date=November 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{BLP sources|date=July 2009}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Gary Beadle\n| image= Gary Beadle.jpg\n| caption= Gary Beadle in 2009, Southend-on-Sea of Paul Johnson.\n| birth_date= 8 July 1965 (age 54)\n| birth_place= [[Bermondsey]], London, England\n| death_date=\n| death_place=  \n| parents= Monica Beadle\n| relatives= [[Rikki Beadle-Blair]] (brother)<br/>[[WSTRN|Louis Rei]] (son)\n| occupation= Actor\n| yearsactive= 1980\u2013present\n| spouse = Tanya Findel-Hawkins (2003\u2013????) <small>Divorced</small>\n| children = 3\n}}\n\n'''Gary Beadle''' (born 8 July 1965) is a British actor, best known for playing [[Paul Trueman]] in ''[[EastEnders]]'' and Gary Barwick in ''[[Operation Good Guys]]''.\n\n==Life and career==\nBeadle was raised as one of five children in [[Bermondsey]], [[South London]],<ref name=AfrApril2016/> where he was baptised a [[Roman Catholic]].<ref name=AfrApril2016/> As children, he and his elder brother [[Rikki Beadle-Blair|Rikki]] produced a version of the 1976 youth musical-gangster film ''[[Bugsy Malone]]'' for [[Southwark London Borough Council]].<ref name=WoS40019/> Directed by Rikki who starred as Talula, Gary played janitor Fizzy.<ref name=AfrApril2016/> Rikki tried to invite the original film's director [[Alan Parker]] to the performance, but his assistant did come, and used her connections to get Rikki, Gary and their younger sister into the community-based [[Anna Scher Theatre]] school.<ref name=WoS40019/>\n\nAfter developing a love of [[hip hop]], and especially [[Run-D.M.C.]] and the [[Sugarhill Gang]], Beadle moved to New York City in his early twenties. On return to London, he formed a rap group called the City Limits Crew. He also worked as a comedian, one half of an act called Swift + 2 Club Bouncers.{{cn|date=January 2020}}\n\nHe also started to work as an actor, and appeared in ''[[The Young Ones (TV series)|The Young Ones]]'' ([[BBC]] 1984); the 1986 film ''[[Absolute Beginners (film)|Absolute Beginners]]''; ''Jerusalem'', the 1987 short film starring the Style Council pop group; ''[[Making Out (TV series)|Making Out]]'' in 1989\u201391 as Simon; the BBC sitcom ''[[Absolutely Fabulous]]'', where he played the gay lover of Eddie's ([[Jennifer Saunders]]) ex-husband Justin; the TV series ''[[Born to Run (TV series)|Born to Run]]'' in 1997; the [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] police drama ''[[The Bill]]'' and BBC medical drama ''[[Casualty (TV series)|Casualty]]'' (2001).\n\nIn 2001 he won the role of [[Paul Trueman]] in ''EastEnders''. A loveable rogue, Beadle left the role when his contract was due to terminate - as he had not appreciated the director and script writers wanting his character to become a drug dealer. He therefore departed from the show and his exit featured the character getting killed off by his gangland boss [[Andy Hunter (EastEnders)|Andy Hunter]] ([[Michael Higgs]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.digitalspy.com/soaps/a17533/eastenders-star-quothatesquot-exit-storyline/|work=[[Digital Spy]]|first=Neil|last=Wilkes|title='EastEnders' star \"hates\" exit storyline|accessdate=2 April 2020|date=10 April 2004}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, he presented the UMA Awards with singer and fellow ex-EastEnders member [[Michelle Gayle]].\n\nImmediately after completing filming of ''EastEnders'', Beadle playing the Evil Queen's henchman in the [[Qdos Entertainment]] production of Snow White at the Cliffs Pavilion in Southend-on-Sea, opposite [[Linda Lusardi]]. Since leaving ''EastEnders'', Beadle has roles in ''[[Holby City]]'' (2005), ''[[Doctors (2000 TV series)|Doctors]]'' (2006) and the [[Jean-Claude Van Damme]] film ''[[Til Death (film)|Til Death]]'', released in 2007.\n\nIn 2007, he appeared in [[BBC Three]] comedy [[Thieves Like Us (TV Series)|Thieves Like Us]]. His brother is actor, writer and performer [[Rikki Beadle-Blair]]. In 2008 he appeared in ''[[The Sarah Jane Adventures]]'' series 2 as [[Clyde Langer]]'s father, [[List of The Sarah Jane Adventures minor characters#Paul Langer|Paul]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gallifreyone.com/news.php#newsitemEkEVyEEEEZymNATHqo |title=The Doctor Who News Page |publisher=Gallifreyone.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080327105740/http://www.gallifreyone.com/news.php#newsitemEkEVyEEEEZymNATHqo |archivedate=27 March 2008 |df= }}</ref> In 2009 he appeared in [[Malice in Wonderland (2009 film)|Malice in Wonderland]] as dj Felix Chester, a Cheshire Cat allusion. In 2010 he appeared in the [[Royal Court Theatre]]'s ''[[Sucker Punch (play)|Sucker Punch]]'' by [[Roy Williams (playwright)|Roy Williams]].\n\nIn 2012 he appeared in ''[[Hustle (TV series)|Hustle]]'' as a police officer.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hustlefans.com/forum/viewtopic.php?f=78&t=5&start=10 |title=Series 8 Guests |website=Hustle Fans Forum |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140305010129/http://www.hustlefans.com/forum/viewtopic.php?f=78&t=5&start=10\n|archivedate=5 March 2014}}</ref> In 2015 he played Docker in BBC One drama ''[[The Interceptor]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/news/a554550/david-gyasi-eastenders-star-jo-joyner-for-bbc-ones-the-interceptor/ |first=Morgan |last=Jeffery |title=David Gyasi, EastEnders star Jo Joyner for BBC One's The Interceptor |website=[[Digital Spy]] |date=28 February 2014 |accessdate=10 September 2017}}</ref> and also featured in the [[Ron Howard]]-directed movie ''[[In the Heart of the Sea (film)|In the Heart of the Sea]]'' which was released in December 2015.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2015-12-21/in-the-heart-of-the-sea-review-a-gruelling-voyage-for-all-concerned |title=In the Heart of the Sea review: 'a gruelling voyage for all concerned' |first=Tom |last=Folley |date=21 December 2015 |magazine=[[Radio Times]] |accessdate=10 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, he starred as Abioseh, an ex-tribesman in the [[Royal National Theatre]]'s production of ''[[Les Blancs]]''.<ref name=AfrApril2016>{{cite web |url=http://www.afridiziak.com/theatrenews/interviews/april2016/gary-beadle.html |title=Gary Beadle, Les Blancs by Lorraine Hansberry \u2013 interview, National Theatre |date=12 April 2016 |first=Gillian |last=Fisher |website=Afridiziak Theatre News |accessdate=10 September 2017}}</ref><ref name=WoS40019>{{cite web |url=http://www.whatsonstage.com/london-theatre/news/5-minutes-with-gary-beadle_40019.html |title=5 minutes with: Gary Beadle \u2013 'When I did EastEnders people said you'll never work again' |first=Emily |last=Cole |date=30 March 2016 |website=What's on Stage |accessdate=10 September 2017}}</ref> He also starred in an episode of the BBC's ''[[Death in Paradise (TV series)|Death in Paradise]]''{{cn|date=January 2020}} and as a [[Detective Chief Inspector]] in ''[[Silent Witness]]''.\n\nIn 2017, Beadle starred as Archdeacon Gabriel Atubo, Rev. Sidney Chambers's boss in Series 3 of [[Grantchester (TV series)|Grantchester]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Grantchester returns to ITV for a third series |url=http://www.itv.com/presscentre/press-releases/grantchester-returns-itv-third-series |date=19 August 2016 |website=ITV Press Centre |accessdate=6 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |title=Meet the cast of Grantchester series three |url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2017-08-04/meet-the-cast-of-grantchester-series-three |first=Sarah |last=Doran |date=4 August 2017 |magazine=Radio Times |accessdate=6 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n* ''[[Absolute Beginners (film)|Absolute Beginners]]'' (1986)\n* ''[[Til Death (film)|Til Death]]'' (2007)\n*[[Malice in Wonderland (2009 film)|Malice in Wonderland]] (2009)\n* ''[[In the Heart of the Sea (film)|In the Heart of the Sea]]'' (2015)\n\n==Television==\n\n* ''[[The Young Ones (TV series)|The Young Ones]]'' (1984)\n* ''[[Casualty (TV series)|Casualty]]'' (1987, 2001 & 2010)\n* ''[[Making Out (TV series)|Making Out]]'' (1989\u20131991)\n* ''[[Absolutely Fabulous]]'' (1992\u20131996)\n* ''[[Born to Run (TV series)|Born to Run]]'' (1997) \n* ''[[Operation Good Guys]]'' (1997\u20131999)\n* ''[[The Bill]]'' (1999)\n* ''[[EastEnders]]'' (2001\u20132004)\n* ''[[Holby City]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[Doctors (2000 TV series)|Doctors]]'' (2006)\n* ''[[Kerching!]]'' (2006)\n* ''[[Thieves Like Us (TV Series)|Thieves Like Us]]'' (2007)\n* ''[[The Sarah Jane Adventures]]'' (2008)\n* ''[[Hustle (TV series)|Hustle]]'' (2012)\n* ''[[The Interceptor]]'' (2015)\n* ''[[Silent Witness]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[Death in Paradise (TV series)|Death in Paradise]]'' (2017)\n* ''[[Grantchester (TV series)|Grantchester]]'' (2017)\n* ''[[[[Summer of Rockets]](TV Series)|Summer of Rockets]]''  (2019)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|name=Gary Beadle|id=0063542}}\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.britishhiphop.co.uk/features/interviews/gary_beadle.html |title=Gary Beadle |website=British Hip Hop |date=28 April 2008}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Beadle, Gary}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English people of Jamaican descent]]\n[[Category:Male actors from London]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Anna Scher Theatre School]]\n[[Category:English male soap opera actors]]\n[[Category:English male television actors]]\n[[Category:English male film actors]]\n[[Category:Black English male actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century English male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century English male actors]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British actor|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{For|the reality TV personality|Gaz Beadle}}\n{{EngvarB|date=November 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{BLP sources|date=July 2009}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Gary Beadle\n| image= Gary Beadle.jpg\n| caption= Gary Beadle in 2009, Southend-on-Sea of Paul Johnson.\n| birth_date= 8 July 1965 (age 54)\n| birth_place= [[Bermondsey]], London, England\n| death_date=\n| death_place=  \n| parents= Monica Beadle\n| relatives= [[Rikki Beadle-Blair]] (brother)<br/>[[WSTRN|Louis Rei]] (son)\n| occupation= Actor\n| yearsactive= 1980\u2013present\n| spouse = Tanya Findel-Hawkins (2003\u2013????) <small>Divorced</small>\n| children = 3\n}}\n\n'''Gary Beadle''' (born 8 July 1965) is a British actor, best known for playing [[Paul Trueman]] in ''[[EastEnders]]'' and Gary Barwick in ''[[Operation Good Guys]]''.\n\n==Life and career==\nBeadle was raised as one of five children in [[Bermondsey]], [[South London]],<ref name=AfrApril2016/> where he was baptised a [[Roman Catholic]].<ref name=AfrApril2016/> As children, he and his elder brother [[Rikki Beadle-Blair|Rikki]] produced a version of the 1976 youth musical-gangster film ''[[Bugsy Malone]]'' for [[Southwark London Borough Council]].<ref name=WoS40019/> Directed by Rikki who starred as Talula, Gary played janitor Fizzy.<ref name=AfrApril2016/> Rikki tried to invite the original film's director [[Alan Parker]] to the performance, but his assistant did come, and used her connections to get Rikki, Gary and their younger sister into the community-based [[Anna Scher Theatre]] school.<ref name=WoS40019/>\n\nAfter developing a love of [[hip hop]], and especially [[Run-D.M.C.]] and the [[Sugarhill Gang]], Beadle moved to New York City in his early twenties. On return to London, he formed a rap group called the City Limits Crew. He also worked as a comedian, one half of an act called Swift + 2 Club Bouncers.{{cn|date=January 2020}}\n\nHe also started to work as an actor, and appeared in ''[[The Young Ones (TV series)|The Young Ones]]'' ([[BBC]] 1984); the 1986 film ''[[Absolute Beginners (film)|Absolute Beginners]]''; ''Jerusalem'', the 1987 short film starring the Style Council pop group; ''[[Making Out (TV series)|Making Out]]'' in 1989\u201391 as Simon; the BBC sitcom ''[[Absolutely Fabulous]]'', where he played the gay lover of Eddie's ([[Jennifer Saunders]]) ex-husband Justin; the TV series ''[[Born to Run (TV series)|Born to Run]]'' in 1997; the [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] police drama ''[[The Bill]]'' and BBC medical drama ''[[Casualty (TV series)|Casualty]]'' (2001).\n\nIn 2001 he won the role of [[Paul Trueman]] in ''EastEnders''. A loveable rogue, Beadle left the role when his contract was due to terminate - as he had not appreciated the director and script writers wanting his character to become a drug dealer. He therefore departed from the show and his exit featured the character getting killed off by his gangland boss [[Andy Hunter (EastEnders)|Andy Hunter]] ([[Michael Higgs]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.digitalspy.com/soaps/a17533/eastenders-star-quothatesquot-exit-storyline/|work=[[Digital Spy]]|first=Neil|last=Wilkes|title='EastEnders' star \"hates\" exit storyline|accessdate=2 April 2020|date=10 April 2004}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, he presented the UMA Awards with singer and fellow ex-EastEnders member [[Michelle Gayle]].\n\nImmediately after completing filming of ''EastEnders'', Beadle playing the Evil Queen's henchman in the [[Qdos Entertainment]] production of Snow White at the Cliffs Pavilion in Southend-on-Sea, opposite [[Linda Lusardi]]. Since leaving ''EastEnders'', Beadle has roles in ''[[Holby City]]'' (2005), ''[[Doctors (2000 TV series)|Doctors]]'' (2006) and the [[Jean-Claude Van Damme]] film ''[[Til Death (film)|Til Death]]'', released in 2007.\n\nIn 2007, he appeared in [[BBC Three]] comedy [[Thieves Like Us (TV Series)|Thieves Like Us]]. His brother is actor, writer and performer [[Rikki Beadle-Blair]]. In 2008 he appeared in ''[[The Sarah Jane Adventures]]'' series 2 as [[Clyde Langer]]'s father, [[List of The Sarah Jane Adventures minor characters#Paul Langer|Paul]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gallifreyone.com/news.php#newsitemEkEVyEEEEZymNATHqo |title=The Doctor Who News Page |publisher=Gallifreyone.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080327105740/http://www.gallifreyone.com/news.php#newsitemEkEVyEEEEZymNATHqo |archivedate=27 March 2008 |df= }}</ref> In 2009 he appeared in [[Malice in Wonderland (2009 film)|Malice in Wonderland]] as dj Felix Chester, a Cheshire Cat allusion. In 2010 he appeared in the [[Royal Court Theatre]]'s ''[[Sucker Punch (play)|Sucker Punch]]'' by [[Roy Williams (playwright)|Roy Williams]].\n\nIn 2012 he appeared in ''[[Hustle (TV series)|Hustle]]'' as a police officer.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hustlefans.com/forum/viewtopic.php?f=78&t=5&start=10 |title=Series 8 Guests |website=Hustle Fans Forum |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140305010129/http://www.hustlefans.com/forum/viewtopic.php?f=78&t=5&start=10\n|archivedate=5 March 2014}}</ref> In 2015 he played Docker in BBC One drama ''[[The Interceptor]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/news/a554550/david-gyasi-eastenders-star-jo-joyner-for-bbc-ones-the-interceptor/ |first=Morgan |last=Jeffery |title=David Gyasi, EastEnders star Jo Joyner for BBC One's The Interceptor |website=[[Digital Spy]] |date=28 February 2014 |accessdate=10 September 2017}}</ref> and also featured in the [[Ron Howard]]-directed movie ''[[In the Heart of the Sea (film)|In the Heart of the Sea]]'' which was released in December 2015.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2015-12-21/in-the-heart-of-the-sea-review-a-gruelling-voyage-for-all-concerned |title=In the Heart of the Sea review: 'a gruelling voyage for all concerned' |first=Tom |last=Folley |date=21 December 2015 |magazine=[[Radio Times]] |accessdate=10 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, he starred as Abioseh, an ex-tribesman in the [[Royal National Theatre]]'s production of ''[[Les Blancs]]''.<ref name=AfrApril2016>{{cite web |url=http://www.afridiziak.com/theatrenews/interviews/april2016/gary-beadle.html |title=Gary Beadle, Les Blancs by Lorraine Hansberry \u2013 interview, National Theatre |date=12 April 2016 |first=Gillian |last=Fisher |website=Afridiziak Theatre News |accessdate=10 September 2017}}</ref><ref name=WoS40019>{{cite web |url=http://www.whatsonstage.com/london-theatre/news/5-minutes-with-gary-beadle_40019.html |title=5 minutes with: Gary Beadle \u2013 'When I did EastEnders people said you'll never work again' |first=Emily |last=Cole |date=30 March 2016 |website=What's on Stage |accessdate=10 September 2017}}</ref> He also starred in an episode of the BBC's ''[[Death in Paradise (TV series)|Death in Paradise]]''{{cn|date=January 2020}} and as a [[Detective Chief Inspector]] in ''[[Silent Witness]]''.\n\nIn 2017, Beadle starred as Archdeacon Gabriel Atubo, Rev. Sidney Chambers's boss in Series 3 of [[Grantchester (TV series)|Grantchester]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Grantchester returns to ITV for a third series |url=http://www.itv.com/presscentre/press-releases/grantchester-returns-itv-third-series |date=19 August 2016 |website=ITV Press Centre |accessdate=6 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |title=Meet the cast of Grantchester series three |url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2017-08-04/meet-the-cast-of-grantchester-series-three |first=Sarah |last=Doran |date=4 August 2017 |magazine=Radio Times |accessdate=6 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n* ''[[Absolute Beginners (film)|Absolute Beginners]]'' (1986)\n* ''[[Til Death (film)|Til Death]]'' (2007)\n*[[Malice in Wonderland (2009 film)|Malice in Wonderland]] (2009)\n* ''[[In the Heart of the Sea (film)|In the Heart of the Sea]]'' (2015)\n\n==Television==\n\n* ''[[The Young Ones (TV series)|The Young Ones]]'' (1984)\n* ''[[Casualty (TV series)|Casualty]]'' (1987, 2001 & 2010)\n* ''[[Making Out (TV series)|Making Out]]'' (1989\u20131991)\n* ''[[Absolutely Fabulous]]'' (1992\u20131996)\n* ''[[Born to Run (TV series)|Born to Run]]'' (1997) \n* ''[[Operation Good Guys]]'' (1997\u20131999)\n* ''[[The Bill]]'' (1999)\n* ''[[EastEnders]]'' (2001\u20132004)\n* ''[[Holby City]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[Doctors (2000 TV series)|Doctors]]'' (2006)\n* ''[[Kerching!]]'' (2006)\n* ''[[Thieves Like Us (TV Series)|Thieves Like Us]]'' (2007)\n* ''[[The Sarah Jane Adventures]]'' (2008)\n* ''[[Hustle (TV series)|Hustle]]'' (2012)\n* ''[[The Interceptor]]'' (2015)\n* ''[[Silent Witness]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[Death in Paradise (TV series)|Death in Paradise]]'' (2017)\n* ''[[Grantchester (TV series)|Grantchester]]'' (2017)\n* ''[[Summer of Rockets(TV Series)|Summer of Rockets]]''  (2019)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|name=Gary Beadle|id=0063542}}\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.britishhiphop.co.uk/features/interviews/gary_beadle.html |title=Gary Beadle |website=British Hip Hop |date=28 April 2008}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Beadle, Gary}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English people of Jamaican descent]]\n[[Category:Male actors from London]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Anna Scher Theatre School]]\n[[Category:English male soap opera actors]]\n[[Category:English male television actors]]\n[[Category:English male film actors]]\n[[Category:Black English male actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century English male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century English male actors]]\n", "name_user": "Jonathan Barrett", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTelevision", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gary_Beadle"}
